ANTI-CORRUPTION GROUPS HOLD MASS AND RALLY AT EDSA SHRINE TO CONDEMN FLOOD CONTROL CORRUPTION

Tindig Pilipinas, NAGKAISA! Labor Coalition, Kalipunan ng Kilusang Masa, Simbahan at Komunidad Laban sa Katiwalian, and other pro-democracy organizations held a mass and rally on Wednesday, September 11, at the historic EDSA Shrine to denounce alleged large-scale corruption in flood control projects.

The groups said billions of pesos intended to shield Filipinos from the impact of floods were lost to ghost projects, kickbacks, and collusion between politicians and contractors. They described the scandal as another betrayal of the Filipino people, particularly the poor and vulnerable who suffer the most during floods and climate disasters.

"We cannot stay silent while our money is being stolen, while our people drown in both floods and corruption," said Kiko Aquino Dee, convenor of Tindig Pilipinas.

"Every peso pocketed by these corrupt officials is a classroom not built, a health center left unfinished, and flood protection denied to our communities. That is why we demand: buuin na ang isang independent commission to investigate this massive corruption, and release the SALNs of all public officials involved. Transparency and accountability must begin now," he added.

Judy Ann Chan Miranda of the NAGKAISA! Labor Coalition said the issue was a matter of moral urgency. "This is not just about corruption, it is about life and death, justice and injustice. The billions stolen from flood control projects could have saved lives and livelihoods. We gather at EDSA Shrine because we believe that, once again, the Filipino people must rise to demand truth, accountability, and reform."

The coalition stressed that the EDSA Shrine—long a symbol of people power against tyranny and abuse—was the rightful venue for Filipinos to declare their stand.

"Our call is simple: end corruption, hold the thieves accountable, and return the money to the people. Gawin nating kadiri muli ang kurapsyon," Dee said.

In the Philippines, the government agencies responsible for flood control and climate change mitigation projects include:

Department of Public Works and Highways (DPWH): This agency is primarily responsible for the construction and maintenance of infrastructure projects, including flood control systems.

Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR): This department handles various environmental protection initiatives and climate change mitigation projects.

Climate Change Commission (CCC): This is the lead policy-making body of the government tasked with coordinating, monitoring, and evaluating programs and action plans related to climate change.

National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC): This council coordinates efforts among various government agencies in disaster risk reduction and management, including flood control and climate change mitigation initiatives.

'HAHA' REACTS TO 'LIBRENG ALMUSAL' IGNORE DUTERTE'S OWN FEEDING LAW

The proposal to reallocate a portion of the government's flood control funds to a Libreng Almusal (free breakfast) program has drawn a flood of "haha" reacts on social media, mostly from DDS or supporters of former President Rodrigo Duterte.

But the ridicule overlooks one important fact: it was Duterte himself who signed into law in 2018 the Masustansyang Pagkain para sa Batang Pilipino Act (Republic Act 11037), which institutionalized a national feeding program for Filipino children in public schools.

Under RA 11037, the government is mandated to implement supplemental feeding for day care children; a school-based feeding program from kindergarten to Grade 6; milk and micronutrient feeding; health examinations, vaccinations, and deworming. The law also requires nutrition education, school vegetable gardens, and even the establishment of a National Nutrition Information System to identify areas with the highest incidence of hunger and undernutrition.

The proposal to expand this effort by funding free breakfast meals from Kindergarten to Senior High School is therefore not new or outlandish—it builds on a framework Duterte himself endorsed to address stunting, malnutrition, and dropout rates, while also boosting farmers' income through direct food purchases as provided in the 2019 Sagip Saka Act.

Critics mocking the idea as impractical ignore both the urgent problem and the precedent: millions of Filipino children remain malnourished, and government has long recognized feeding programs as a matter of law and policy.

The debate is not about whether children should be fed nutritious meals—it's about whether public funds are being spent on the right priorities.
